<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peace Commission Head on Dialogue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1601011294 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 0030 
GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1601011294 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Juan Carlos Santoyo; from the "Vector 21" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] Manuel Camacho Solis, head of a special commission 
for peace and reconciliation in Chiapas State, held a news 
conference on 14 January before heading for Mexico City where, 
according to Camacho, he will make consultations and meet with 
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari. 
  He made important statements about the peace dialogue in 
this 
state. Camacho said that the outlook has changed; peace should 
not involve a restoration of the status quo but the solution of 
the political-military problem. It should also involve an 
orderly and institutional leadership in the countryside, he 
added. 
  Camacho said that we must implement the necessary measures 
to 
effect peace in Chiapas, but this should not be the result of a 
conventional negotiation of the conflict. He said that there 
are many beliefs and issues that still trouble the residents and 
undermine peace in Chiapas. 
  The commissioner said that Chiapas residents must analyze 
these beliefs and issues. He added that changes must be 
made--for example, changes to the Penal Code. Camacho said that 
we must open a formal negotiation process by ensuring that the 
conditions that are established will enable the parties involved 
to reach the goal. 
  He said that the government and local leaders must make 
legislative changes, but only Chiapas residents should determine 
which changes must be made. Camacho added that the most 
important thing at this time is to ensure that united efforts in 
this state will achieve security, justice, and democracy. 
  We now know who will be the mediator; that is, the direct 
contact between the special commission for peace and 
reconciliation headed by Manuel Camacho Solis and the Zapatista 
National Liberation Army [EZLN]. That person will be Bishop 
Samuel Ruiz. Camacho said that Ruiz is a valuable and highly 
respected person in the state and was proposed as mediator by 
the EZLN. He will be the direct link in the process to 
determine whether the interlocutors that the EZLN selected are 
valid and whether peace can be negotiated with them, Camacho 
added: 
  [Begin Camacho recording] The EZLN, via public communiques, 
has proposed Samuel Ruiz, the bishop of San Cristobal de las 
Casas, as mediator. I think that the bishop's participation in 
this process, along with the other Chiapas bishops, will be 
important. Any idea or proposal received through Ruiz will be 
immediately considered. 
  As I said upon arriving in San Cristobal, it will take some 
time to restore peace in Chiapas. If we managed, however, to 
turn into a clear political concept the efforts of the civilian 
movement for peace, the unification of Chiapas residents to 
achieve security, justice, and democracy, state and municipal 
institutions, the decisions of the federal Executive Branch, 
work in communities and organizations, pastoral reconciliation 
messages, open and objective information, the efforts of the 
churches, and the role of the Congress of the Union what seems 
impossible could become reality. [sentence as heard] [end 
recording] 
  Camacho added that only the combination of everyone's 
goodwill, intelligence, and honesty will prevent the outcome of 
this conflict from resembling those that have harmed other 
countries in Central America. He said that at this time peace 
must be built via specific dialogue. 
  Ruiz gave thanks for this responsibility, which he described 
as a very heavy burden we must shoulder. He added: I will try 
to reconcile my pastoral duties with my mediator duties. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

