<H3> <TI>   Colosio Calls For Campaign To End Poverty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1501022594 Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 
0435 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1501022594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City XEW Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] In Queretaro, Luis Donaldo Colosio, Institutional 
Revolutionary Party [PRI] presidential candidate, has just ended 
his first campaign tour. He visited Pedro Escobedo and San Juan 
del Rio and later went to Hidalgo. Pablo Martin Contreras, 
president of the Otomi people, gave Colosio the staff of command 
in Ixmiquilpan, in the heart of the Mezquital Valley, where 
Colosio received the support of the Indian population. In 
downtown Ixmiquilpan he met with PRI members from Hidalgo. He 
said that what is most painful is learning first hand the 
difficult conditions that many Mexican communities face daily. 
He added that shortages are intolerable and cannot be accepted 
and that poverty should not be accepted as one's destiny. 
  At an event attended by thousands of peasants, Colosio 
emphasized that things must be called by their names because 
Mexico rejects lies and demagoguery, which are deceptive. The 
PRI candidate called for a decisive battle to end poverty, 
deprivation, and inequality in Mexico. He also talked about the 
Chiapas situation. 
  [Begin Colosio recording] In the difficult times that 
Chiapas State is experiencing, we must all reiterate our desire, 
our fervent desire, and our determination to have only one 
Mexico. To face the challenge of poverty, the fatherland needs 
unity, harmony, and work. This is what the gleam of hope in the 
eyes of Hidalgo children, of Chiapas children, and of all 
Mexican children is asking. [end recording] 
  Colosio said that the Chiapas and Mezquital Valley 
situations 
demonstrate the urgent need for more just conditions. He 
added that the solution is sweeping social reform. 
  [Begin Colosio recording] Today we are encouraged by 
progress in the negotiations. The Mexican Army's declaration of 
a cease-fire shows willingness to find ways to bring peace to 
this Mexican region. [end recording] 
  Colosio pointed out that talks, reconciliation, and the 
strengthening of the state of law will continue to promote 
stability in Mexico. Later, he met with the PRI political 
council in Pachuca and with Hidalgo women. He also attended a 
social event. 

</TEXT>

