<H3> <TI>   PAN Asks Candidates Not To Capitalize on Chiapas Events </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1501043694 Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 
0435 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1501043694 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City XEW Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] In Mexico City the PAN [National Action Party] 
candidate said that other presidential candidates should not use 
the Chiapas situation to their benefit. During the weekly PAN 
news conference, presidential candidate Diego Fernandez de 
Cevallos spoke about events in Chiapas and called on other 
presidential candidates: 
  [Begin Fernandez de Cevallos recording] In view of the 
latest 
violent events in Chiapas, I believe there should be, not only 
from me but from all presidential candidates, respect and basic 
prudence not to take advantage of this painful moment to try and 
gain an advantage. [end recording] 
  The other topic discussed during the PAN news conference had 
to do with the presidential candidates' debates. Fernandez de 
Cevallos rejected the proposal that the nine candidates debate 
in two sessions. 
  [Begin Fernandez de Cevallos recording] I said that I do not 
reject that all candidates appear. What I protest is the 
intention to reduce the discussion of the country's major 
conflicts and topics to only two appearances. It is not 
possible, even with the country's modern communications system 
and especially with the high expectations generated, that these 
debates be reduced to two appearances for all presidential 
candidates. It is not fair, it is not correct, and it is not 
democratic. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

