<H3> <TI>   Tello: U.S. Congress Summons `Offensive' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1501203494 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1929 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1501203494 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Mexico City, 15 Jan (EFE) -- Mexican Foreign 
Secretary Manuel Tello last night described as offensive to 
Mexico a proposal by U.S. Representative Robert Torricelli, a 
Democrat, that the U.S. Congress investigate the Chiapas events. 
  Torricelli is calling on Clinton administration officials 
and 
human rights advocates to testify at a hearing on the Chiapas 
uprising. 
  "The United States should make very clear to the Mexican 
Government the type of political reforms required if we are to 
maintain a new relationship," stated the Democratic 
representative, who said the hearing has been scheduled for 2 
February. 
  Tello said Torricelli's initiative is unfriendly and 
offensive. It seems that the legislator is unaware, Tello 
stated, of the measures the Mexican Government has taken to find 
a peaceful solution to the conflict in Chiapas. 
  It seems that they want to take up the old arguments that 
went on during the NAFTA debate and link commercial policies to 
interventionist intentions in Mexico, the foreign relations 
secretary concluded. [no quotation marks as received] 
  A group of U.S. legislators who support NAFTA have sent a 
letter to President Carlos Salinas de Gortari to express their 
concern over the events in Chiapas and to ask him to facilitate 
investigations by human rights groups and the media in the area 
of conflict. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

