<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serra, U.S. and Canadian Officials Hold News Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1601133094 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 0030 
GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1601133094 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vector 21" newscast] </F>
  [Excerpts] The U.S. trade representative [Mickey Kantor] 
and the Canadian minister of international trade [Roy MacLaren] 
agreed at a news conference that the Mexican Government alone 
must resolve the armed conflict in Chiapas State by acting 
wisely to restore social peace. MacLaren said the Mexican 
Government must be cautious to achieve a peaceful solution. 
  [Begin MacLaren recording] I hope the Mexican Government's 
good sense and wisdom will lead to the prompt resolution of the 
conflict in Chiapas. [end recording] 
  Mickey Kantor said his government has no reason to meddle in 
the internal affairs of other nations, but nothing can prevent 
the United States from observing the events that take place in 
other nations. [passage omitted] 
  Jaime Serra Puche, Mexican Secretary of Commerce and 
Industrial Development, was also present at the news conference 
and said that a society can progress only if there is social 
peace. 
  [Begin Serra Puche recording] Every sector of Mexican 
society should try to create a harmonious atmosphere that will 
allow our society and economy to operate in peace and stability 
and sufficiently free from concern so we can enjoy continued 
progress and growth and improve the distribution of our 
country's wealth. Every Mexican must make this effort. [end 
recording] 
  Aside from political issues, the commerce secretaries 
announced that this was the first meeting held since NAFTA went 
into effect and that it marked the inauguration of the Free 
Trade Agreement Commission, which will be headed by the Mexican 
commerce secretary, the U.S. trade representative, and the 
Canadian international trade minister. The commission will be 
based in Mexico. Plans for opening other commissions were also 
set into motion. 
  Serra, Kantor, and MacLaren agreed to meet on 15 April in 
Morocco within the framework of the conclusion of the GATT 
Uruguay Round. 
  The officials also discussed the possible participation of 
other nations in NAFTA, but no conclusions were reached. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

