<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Value-Added Tax Temporarily Suspended at Retail Level </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1701170994 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 1550 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1701170994 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Decentralization Minister Allan Brewer Carias 
announced that the Council of Ministers decided last night to 
suspend the VAT [value-added tax] at the retail level until 
merchants obtain authorization from the Finance Ministry to use 
cash registers that have been adjusted to include the new tax. 
Brewer said the Council of Ministers decided to reform Article 
2 of the VAT and that merchants must request the necessary 
authorization from the Finance Ministry prior to 28 February. 
He added that consumers cannot be charged the VAT until 
merchants obtain the authorization and duly display it in their 
stores and outlets. 
  [Begin Brewer recording] This means that retail merchants 
cannot charge consumers the VAT until they obtain the proper 
authorization. Of course, any VAT collected up to this point 
must be turned over to the National Treasury. The Tax Office 
will fine merchants according to the current tax law if they 
violate this law in any way. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

