<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fujimori: Sabotage Not Ruled Out in Helicopter Crash </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1401193894 Lima Global de Television Network in Spanish 
0100 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1401193894 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima Global de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Global TV News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] After expressing his sympathies to relatives of the 
victims of the helicopter crash, President Fujimori said no 
possibilities can be rejected in cases of this sort and would 
not rule out sabotage as the cause of the accident. Fujimori 
added that his government will not reconsider the sanctions 
imposed on Chilean MRTA [Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement] 
members. 
  [Begin recording] [Fujimori] I reject the report saying that 
the helicopter crash was caused by a fuel shortage or poor 
maintenance. Accidents of this sort happen by chance and are 
regrettable. They must be investigated in a strictly technical 
manner. The Air Force has appointed an investigative commission 
to investigate the accident. The reasons for the crash 
helicopter must be clearly outlined, because according to the 
control tower, the helicopter was landing as usual with no 
problems. 
  [Unidentified reporter] Is it possible to investigate the 
reasons for a possible sabotage of this helicopter? 
  [Fujimori] No possibilities can or should be ruled out. I 
had even planned to fly to Cuzco before going to Arequipa. I 
flew with the crew of that helicopter a week ago and everything 
was normal. I think this was a rather unexpected event. The 
investigations must be thorough to eliminate all possibilities 
other than technical or circumstantial reasons. 
  Regarding the Chilean MRTA members, they did not perpetrate 
these hideous crimes in Chile but in Peru, and they have been 
sentenced to life imprisonment. I reiterate: I will not 
reverse my position. They have been tried according to 
antiterrorist laws. The Peruvian position on this is clear: 
Peru has a right to peace. 
  [Reporter] Will the sentences be reconsidered? 
  [Fujimori] Not at all. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

