<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Drug Trafficker's Capture Compared to Guzman's </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1501031094 Lima Radio Programas del Peru Network in 
Spanish 1800 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1501031094 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima Radio Programas del Peru Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Newspaper of the Airwaves, Second Edition" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] President Alberto Fujimori has announced that drug 
trafficker Demetrio Chavez Penaherrera, also known as El 
Vaticano, will receive a life sentence. The president said that 
the drug trafficker, who was deported from Colombia, was one of 
the leading drug traffickers in Alto Huallaga and his capture is 
comparable to Abimael Guzman's. 
  [Begin recording] [Fujimori] Chavez Penaherrera moved 
approximately 30 tons of drugs monthly and had his own airport 
in Campanilla. Every month he made approximately 40 flights and 
collected a total of $30 million. He was the main cocaine 
supplier for the Cali Cartel, which, in turn, exported almost 90 
percent of that cocaine to the (?United States). In short, this 
has truly been a harsh blow to the drug trade. 
  [Unidentified reporter] What sentence will he get? 
  [Fujimori] We have passed very timely legislation on drug 
trafficking. Now we can give El Vaticano the maximum sentence: 
life in prison. There can be no doubt of that. I believe that 
for narcoterrorism, El Vaticano's capture is comparable to that 
of Abimael Guzman. 
  [Reporter] [question indistinct] 
  [Fujimori] I repeat, two. (?Lacalinia and Caloveda) are 
brothers who have already been captured. There is an entire 
network of people who are involved and they have either been 
captured or are being investigated. This capture constitutes a 
terrible setback for narcoterrorism. [end recording] 
  This is what President Fujimori said at the closing of the 
academic year at the National Fine Arts School. The president 
announced that a new fine arts institute is going to be built. 

</TEXT>

