<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   De Leon Writes Clinton on Revision of Self-Defense Patrols </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1801043594 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 0125 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1801043594 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 17 Jan (ACAN-EFE) -- Guatemalan 
President Ramiro de Leon Carpio explained today to his U.S. 
colleague, Bill Clinton, the decision to revise the functions of 
the Civilian Self-Defense Patrols [PAC], state paramilitary 
groups that humanitarian organizations accuse of violating human 
rights. 
  In a letter addressed today to Clinton and released by the 
Presidency Public Relations Office, De Leon said that he has 
ordered turning the PAC, which operate in areas that are no 
longer indispensable, into "Peace and Development Committees." 
  The patrols, which consist of civilians whom the Army equips 
and controls, were created during the defacto government of 
General Efrain Rios Montt (1982-83) to fight the guerrillas in 
the interior. 
  These groups, made up mostly of Indians, have been accused 
by 
national and international humanitarian organizations of 
committing abuses against the indigenous population, which is 
why they have demanded that the government dissolve them. 
  General Mario Enriquez, Guatemalan defense minister, has 
recognized that the Army has some 520,000 patrolmen in various 
parts of the country, supporting 40,000 soldiers of the Armed 
Forces. 
  In the letter, de Leon also tells Clinton of the "first big 
objective" of his agenda, which is to consolidate democracy and 
the state of law "as a part of political order," for which he 
appreciates the "support and permanent backing of the United 
States." 
  For it, he says, there is a commitment to respect human 
rights and the multicultural reality of the country, to fight 
impunity and corruption, to promote decentralization, and to 
promote the people's participation. 
  He also informed him of the recommendations by Christian 
Tomuschat, an expert UN human rights adviser, which have been 
fulfilled, such as the restructuring of the presidential general 
staff, a military group that was also accused of serious abuses 
and telephone espionage. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-51339 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat011_g_94002" </HT>


