<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Employees Protest Planned Referendum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1501005694 Guatemala City Teleonce Television in Spanish 
1900 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1501005694 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City Teleonce Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Telepress" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Public workers began a series of demonstrations 
today, Friday, against a referendum slated for 30 January. 
Trade unions, human rights defense groups, and other people's 
organizations staged a demonstration to voice their opposition 
to the referendum, claiming that the changes to the Constitution 
do not meet their expectations. 
  The government employees unions which demonstrated this 
morning demanded a 40-percent salary increase, claiming that the 
price increases for consumer basket articles are extremely high 
compared to current salaries. Leaders of the government 
employees unions that participated in the demonstration 
announced that they are calling on all government employees 
unions to participate in a strike on 28 January. 
  The demonstration, which was slated to begin at 0900, did 
not 
start until 1030 because the demonstrators did not arrive on 
time. The leaders were forced to make emergency calls to begin 
the march that left from the El Trebol area and went down 
Bolivar Avenue to the downtown area. The demonstration ended at 
the main plaza. 
  The national police carefully watched the demonstration to 
prevent any infiltrations by other individuals. There were no 
problems during the demonstration. 

</TEXT>

