<F P=100> Paraguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wasmosy, Franco Discuss Border Trade Problems </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1801150094 Asuncion ABC COLOR in Spanish 18 Jan 94 p 17 </F>
<F P=103> PY1801150094 </F>
<F P=104>  Asuncion ABC COLOR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by unidentified correspondents in Colonia, Uruguay] </F>
  [Text] Paraguayan President Juan Carlos Wasmosy has 
obtained assurances from his Brazilian counterpart Itamar Franco 
that customs restrictions to bilateral trade enforced by 
Brazilian officials that amount to a virtual intimidation 
campaign -- through the confiscation of commodities purchased 
by Brazilian citizens at the Paraguayan city of Ciudad del Este 
-- "will be immediately revised and that the appropriate 
corrective measures will be adopted to end this situation that 
runs contrary to the integration process between Paraguay and 
Brazil." 
  Early yesterday morning, before the opening of the Mercosur 
[Common Market of the South] summit, Wasmosy conveyed this 
problem to Franco based on a protest note submitted to him by 
Ciudad del Este Mayor Guillermo Campuzano and by the Foz do 
Yguazu-based Parana-Paraguay Chamber of Commerce. The note 
charges Brazilian customs officials with a harassment campaign 
"that has caused a major reduction in the flow of tourists to 
Foz do Yguazu and Ciudad del Este, with the subsequent reduction 
in sales for stores, hotels, and restaurants." The drop in 
business has been estimated at nearly 40 percent. 

</TEXT>

