<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Onusal Denies Plans To Leave Country After March Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1901001394 San Salvador Canal Doce Television in Spanish 
0300 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1901001394 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador Canal Doce Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Mario Jovel from the "Up to Date" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Augusto Ramirez Ocampo, chief of the UN Observers 
for El Salvador [Onusal], has clarified that his mission will 
leave the country at the conclusion of the peace agreement 
verification process and not immediately after the elections, as 
one local newspaper has reported. According to the diplomat, 
the Onusal mandate will continue past the March elections. 
  [Begin Ramirez Ocampo recording] Onusal's obligation is to 
verify the peace agreements, and therefore Onusal's duration is 
determined by compliance with the agreements. [end recording] 
  Ramirez Ocampo said the concern some political sectors have 
over the limited number of party representatives on department 
boards has been resolved by a bill that the Supreme Electoral 
Tribunal presented Monday to the Legislative Assembly. 
  According to the Onusal spokesman, the bill states that all 
the parties, including the coalitions, can have a party 
representative in both the department and the municipal boards. 
  [Begin Ramirez Ocampo recording] It is obvious that no party 
can be deprived of representation, but it is also obvious, I 
believe, that there cannot be more than one representative. 
This means that it is important that all contending political 
parties are represented equally at the electoral department 
boards. [end recording] 
  As Ocampo sees it, it must be guaranteed that the electoral 
department and municipal boards function legally. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

