<F P=100> Uruguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   General Mermot Sanctioned With `Strict Arrest' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1801235394 Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in Spanish 
12 Jan 94 p 6 </F>

<F P=103> PY1801235394 </F>
<F P=104>  Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A military source told EL OBSERVADOR that General 
Raul Mermot has been sanctioned with 10 days of strict arrest by 
the Army commander in chief, but he will continue as commander 
of the Third Army Division based in Tacuarembo because the 
sanction is to be applied "without hindering his present 
function." 
  The sources minimized the importance of the sanction that 
will end on 17 January. A military source said Mermot "has the 
command channels open" and he, therefore, continues "commanding 
the division." 
  The source said Mermot is a member of the Supreme Tribunal 
on 
Promotions and Resources, adding that for the past 30 days he 
has been working at Army Command headquarters, where he 
currently is serving his strict arrest. 
  "The sanction of strict arrest is continuous for a period. 
Then we have, according to the characteristics of the violation, 
suspensions, reassignments, reassignment suspensions, and trial 
by military justice," the source said. 
  Lieutenant General Daniel Garcia, Army commander in chief, 
said Gen. Mermot's sanction is an Army "internal and 
administrative issue." A military source added: "The fact that 
a general has been sanctioned does not mean it did not happen 
before or that it will not happen again." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

