<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mayors Meet in Caracas To Discuss VAT, Decentralization </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1401220194 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 1550 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1401220194 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] President Ramon Velasquez opened the meeting of 
mayors this morning, and state decentralization will be the main 
topic of discussion. For the first time an administrative 
mechanism has been created that allows cooperation and 
coordination between central and regional governments. The 
value-added tax [VAT] and its application also became a leading 
topic of discussion at the meeting. 
  [Begin recording] [Caracas Mayor Aristobulo Isturiz] We 
demand what the Constitution stipulates. The Constitution says 
that all taxes must have a common characteristic; that is, they 
must be progressive and fair. In other words, people who earn 
more should pay more taxes; those who earn less should pay less; 
and those who have nothing should pay nothing. That is fair. 
The VAT taxes everyone equally. People who earn more pay the 
same as those who earn nothing. This policy has critical 
consequences because the Venezuelan Constitution still stresses 
the role of the state by noting that the state has 
responsibilities toward the citizens and that the citizens have 
basic rights. 
  [Maracaibo Mayor Fernando Chumaceiro] The process of 
administrative decentralization, which basically had been a 
transfer of power from the central government to the state 
governments, has been expanded. This is positive progress, but 
it is insufficient. Full decentralization takes place once 
decentralization reaches municipal levels, and then from 
municipal levels to parochial levels. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

