<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bazin Favors National Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1801225394 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1145 
GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1801225394 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Following the conference in Miami, one more voice 
is being raised in favor of the national conference in Haiti. 
  Former Prime Minister Marc Bazin has chosen the U.S. 
newspaper THE MIAMI HERALD to voice his support for holding such 
a national conference. The idea of a national conference is 
nothing new. It has already been conducted in many countries, 
and the results are positive,, writes the leader for the 
Movement For the Establishment of Democracy, Marc Bazin. He 
states in his article that there is no other peaceful and 
reasonable alternative than the national conference. The return 
to guerrilla techniques would be devastating and would only 
facilitate the return to dictatorship. On the other hand, to use 
and manipulate the tragedy of the boat people in order to take 
power would be completely inexcusable, inhumane and 
reprehensible. We are quoting some excerpts from Marc Bazin's 
article in THE MIAMI HERALD of 16 January. The former prime 
minister concludes, quote: A national conference should be, 
above all, an invitation to a realistic, fair and practical 
compromise, 
unquote. 

</TEXT>

