<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Campa Announces Sale of Vaccine to Argentina </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1501031594 Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks in 
Spanish 0100 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1501031594 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Dr. Conception Campa, director of the Finlay 
Institute, has announced that this afternoon Cuban authorities 
received the document authorizing Cuba to freely market its 
meningococcal meningitis vaccine in Argentina. 
  [Begin recording] As you all know, this has been a long 
struggle which has taken many complex turns in terms of its 
approval or rejection. There was great pressure exerted by the 
Argentine people, by pediatricians, and by mothers who wanted to 
vaccinate their children. 
  Up to now, no permit had been issued to register the 
vaccine; 
therefore, there was no permit to sell it or to let the people 
buy it. This is what the great news we received a few minutes 
ago is about. I received a call telling me that we already have 
the registration in our hands. This opens the doors to freely 
market the vaccine and for the mothers to buy it and vaccinate 
their children, for the pediatricians to recommend it. 
  Up to now we were not able to do this. This represent an 
important step to protect those children who are in the midst of 
a full blown epidemic and who were not allowed to get the 
vaccine. This is also something very important for us: To be 
able to sell a product which offers no risks and has extremely 
high potential to fight that epidemic in Argentine. [end 
recording] 
  Dr. Concepcion Campa received today the 23 October award 
from 
the Federation of Cuban Women, a homage to the Cuban woman who 
gives to science and Cuba the best of her intellect. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

