<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Governor Appointed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1901022494 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 0044 
GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1901022494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Maricarmen Camacho from Tuxtla Gutierrez, Chiapas] </F>
  [Text] This afternoon [18 January], the 58th legislature of 
the Chiapas Congress appointed Javier Lopez Moreno governor of 
Chiapas after Provisional Governor Elmar Setzer resigned. After 
being sworn in as governor, Lopez Moreno announced that the 
state's three branches will be installed as soon as possible in 
Ocosingo in an effort to deal with the institutional crisis in 
the state. The new governor promised to be frank and to deal 
directly with the Chiapas Indians and peasants, and he invited 
the people to confront the crisis with unity, genius, and hard 
work. He said he will hold the post of governor loyally and 
patriotically. 
  [Begin Lopez Moreno recording] I will take office with the 
state's legislative and judicial branches in Ocosingo as soon as 
possible. The new government will begin working in the middle 
of the conflict zone with all of the forces of Chiapas. [end 
recording] 
  The appointment was made by a congressional majority. The 
only vote against Lopez Moreno was cast by PRD [Party of the 
Democratic Revolution] Deputy Demostenes Munoz who, attempting 
to be funny and ironic, voted for Commander Marcos -- the leader 
of the subversive actions in the jungle areas of Chiapas. 
  The new governor is of Indian heritage, and he was born in 
Tenejapa on 19 November 1946. He holds a law degree from the 
Mexican Autonomous University. He served as education and 
culture secretary during the government of retired General 
Absalon Castellanos Dominguez. For several years he was member 
of the PRI's [Institutional Revolutionary Party] National 
Executive Committee, where he held the posts of social action 
secretary, delegate to the Federal Electoral Commission, and 
head of the PRI's National Executive Committee advisers. In 
addition, he served as federal deputy for Chiapas during the 
54th legislature of the Chiapas Congress. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

