<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Banana Bloc Shows First Sign of Split </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1401175994 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 0024 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1401175994 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] San Jose, 13 Jan (ACAN-EFE) -- The solid bloc 
maintained by the Latin American banana-producing countries in 
their negotiations with the European Union (EU) has shown its 
first public fissure when four countries in the bloc failed to 
attend today's meeting in Costa Rica to study the European 
import proposal. 
  The meeting, which ends tonight, was called by Costa Rica. 
However, Ecuador, the world's top banana-producing country; 
Panama; Honduras; and Guatemala were not present, and only the 
host country, Colombia, Venezuela, and Nicaragua showed up for 
the meeting. 
  Prior to the meeting, which got under way after an hour's 
delay, Costa Rican Foreign Trade Minister Roberto Rojas said the 
countries that had not attended the meeting "do not agree" on 
presenting a counterproposal to the EU's 14 December offer, 
which is now being studied in San Jose. 

</TEXT>

