<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gaviria Responds to Senators on Presence of U.S. Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1201193994 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1201193994 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National" newscast] </F>
  [Text] President Cesar Gaviria does not want to get 
involved in the argument over the presence of U.S. troops in the 
country. Superficially and without going into details, he has 
responded to those who have dared to question the presence of 
these troops in the country. The U.S. troops are already in 
Juanchaco, but the debate on whether their presence should have 
received Senate approval is just beginning to get hot. 
  [Begin Senator Alfredo Vasquez Carrizosa recording] What is 
understood by the term troops is an armed and trained group 
under the command of an officer and the flag of a certain 
country. This is exactly what came to Colombia. [end recording] 
  Notwithstanding, the president told Senators Fabio Valencia 
and Gustavo Rodriguez, who demanded an explanation, the 
construction of a school and a health center did not merit a 
report to the Senate. 
  [Begin Senator Rodriguez recording] As a result of this 
theory or subterfuge by the president, which I believe is an 
effort to disregard the Constitution, we are yielding our 
national sovereignty to foreign troops, no more and no less. 
[end recording] 
  In addition, the Defense Ministry explained the entry of 
U.S. 
troops is backed by a mutual assistance defense agreement signed 
in 1952. 
  [Begin Carrizosa recording] The Constitution takes priority 
over any agreement signed by the Defense Ministry in 1952 and 
the Constitution demands permission from the Senate. [end 
recording] 
  While the controversy continues, 259 U.S. soldiers are in 
various parts of the country working on construction projects in 
spite of the opposition. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

