<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Policy Adviser Comments on Gaviria OAS Candidacy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1301003494 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1301003494 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Gustavo Rodriguez Vargas, a member of the Foreign 
Relations Advisory Commission, said today [11 January] that the 
OAS secretary generalship cannot be attained by ceding Colombian 
sovereignty. Rodriguez Vargas said that there is a need for a 
clearer policy regarding cases such as the presence of U.S. 
Marines in Juanchaco, on the Atlantic coast, and the incident 
involving the incursion by Venezuelan troops in Saravena, 
Arauca. In the case of Venezuela, Colombia has been too 
complaisant regarding the defense of our sovereignty. Some 
believe that President Cesar Gaviria is seeking the neighboring 
country's vote for the post of OAS secretary general, and have 
gone as far as to publish cartoons such as these. 
  [Begin Rodriguez recording] I hope President Gaviria does 
become the OAS secretary general, but it should not be at the 
expense of our national sovereignty. [end recording] 
  According to Gustavo Rodriguez, six of the seven meetings 
the 
commission has held have addressed the Venezuelan issue. 
Colombia first stepped back fearing Carlos Andres Perez' fall 
from power. Then it desisted in favor of the election process in 
Venezuela, and finally because of pressure from the Venezuelan 
press. SEMANA magazine reported on Gaviria's recent efforts. 
It says he spent his vacation on the telephone trying to 
recruit votes for the secretary generalship. He was after the 
votes of Costa Rica, Nicaragua, Panama, Ecuador, and, of course, 
Venezuela, which has Miguel Angel Burelli running for that same 
post. According to the magazine, Gaviria even contacted 
Burelli. Experts on international policy believe Venezuela will 
support Costa Rica, and its candidate Bernd Neihaus, instead of 
Colombia. They would benefit more by supporting a Caribbean 
candidate than a Colombian. Experts also say that President 
Gaviria must choose between his aspirations at the OAS and 
defending national sovereignty. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

