<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Robaina Says Multipartyism Unimportant </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1401173094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1943 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1401173094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 13 Jan (EFE) -- Today, Cuban Foreign 
Minister Roberto Robaina said he has never heard multipartyism 
discussed at Cuban Government meetings because it is an issue 
that is "not very serious" and "lacks importance." 
  "Our meetings are characterized by their substantial 
agendas; 
there is no time for such unimportant issues," Robaina said in 
the second part of an interview published today by EL SOL DE 
MEXICO. "Thoughts about multipartyism are not among our 
country's many priorities at this time," Robaina added. 
  Asked if there has been any reaction within the government 
to 
exiled Cubans' statements supporting multipartyism, the Cuban 
foreign minister responded: "From the time I began participating 
in the meetings, an issue of such little importance has never 
been on the agenda. The historical reasons that joined us into a 
single party are stronger today than ever." 
  Robaina asserted, "There used to be multipartyism in Cuba 
and 
all those parties did very little to resolve the considerable 
problems our society had experienced for over half a century." 

</TEXT>

