<F P=100> Inter-Caribbean Affairs </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   ACP Regains Chamber Control; Monde Elected President </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1401171494 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1130 
GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1401171494 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] As of 13 January in the Haitian parliament, it is 
Frantz Robert Monde, author of the clean-sweep policy [politique 
de la table rase] who now occupies the position of head of the 
Chamber of Deputies. 
  Monde, who has coveted the presidency of the chamber since 
the beginning of the legislature, has acquired the post thanks 
to a compromise by the socialists, and by members of the 
Alliance for Parliamentary Cohesion, ACP, to the detriment of 
outgoing President Antoine Joseph of the Movement for the 
Establishment of Democracy in Haiti. 
  The National Front for Change and Democracy [FNCD] 
parliamentarians admit that they are dissatisfied with this 
choice. In the opinion of some, this election confirms the 
strong tendency toward the clean sweep prevailing in the 
Chamber. Difficult days are expected. Bob Monde is a resolute, 
avowed, fierce opponent of exiled President Jean-Bertrand 
Aristide. Several FNCD and centrist parliamentarians say they 
fear the future with such a choice. Bob Monde will be assisted 
by socialist Mac-Ferl Morquette as vice-president. It is 
Emmanuel Reyme, the Haitian Christian Democratic Party man, 
another fierce opponent to the exiled president, who has been 
elected first secretary. The ACP has thus resumed control of the 
chamber. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

