<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Heeds Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1201192794 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 1816 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1201192794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 12 Jan (DPA) -- The National Defense 
Secretariat today reported that the Mexican Army is heeding a 
unilateral cease-fire ordered by President Carlos Salinas de 
Gortari in the conflict zone in the state of Chiapas. It 
pointed out that the Army and Air Force "will not open fire 
except against armed groups who attack them, who directly 
jeopardize the civilian population, or who seek to return to 
positions and towns they had occupied." 
  In an official communique, the secretariat added, "the Air 
Force, in particular, will cease fire except in cases of attacks 
on Army personnel in uninhabited areas where they require help." 
  President Salinas de Gortari had said he decided to "suspend 
all fire" in the conflict area because the Army already 
fulfilled "the initial goal" of its mission to restore control 
and security in the region. 
  In the communique, which was issued immediately after the 
presidential announcement, the Defense Secretariat pointed out 
that the troops "will continue to protect towns that requested 
help to prevent any possible aggressions." The communique said, 
"they will not allow these armed people to move outside the 
region," and it added, "they will maintain free mobility in 
terms of personnel and equipment, including ground and aerial 
reconnaisance operations." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

