<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peace Commissioner Discusses Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1201204494 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1900 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1201204494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1900 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "At Noon" newscast] </F>
  [Text] A news conference by Manuel Camacho Solis, 
commissioner for peace and reconciliation in Chiapas State, has 
just ended. At approximately 1230, Camacho Solis disclosed three 
points to reaching an agreement for normalcy, peace, calm, and 
tranquillity in this area. 
  He said the first step had been taken by the chief of the 
executive branch. This step consists of suspending any 
confrontation between the Army and the rebels. The second step, 
Camacho explained, is for all parties to join in a civic 
movement to lay the groundwork for negotiations. We then would 
go on to the third step, which will be the dialogue. 
  According to Camacho Solis, a great politician who favors 
dialogue, what is needed is a dialogue with the Chiapas 
guerrillas to discuss their viewpoints and demands and then set 
a deadline. With regard to a deadline, he noted that a deadline 
for the Zapatist National Liberation Army [EZLN] cannot be 
established yet because they are in no condition for that. He 
said all he wants is for the situation to move toward one of 
peace, tranquillity, and calm in Chiapas State. Camacho Solis 
said: We are certain that we are doing fine; we are on the 
correct path to reconciliation. 
  Camacho Solis is about to start a motorcade for peace. It 
will depart from San Cristobal de las Casas and go to Ocosingo, 
where heavy fighting with the EZLN took place. 
  During the news conference, Camacho Solis was accompanied by 
Bishop Samuel Ruiz and Armed Forces Commander Oton Calderon. 

</TEXT>

