<H3> <TI>   New Foreign Secretary Says Chiapas Events Affect Image Abroad </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1201205594 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 1940 
GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1201205594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Marcela Gutierrez from the "Vector 21" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Relations Secretary Manuel Tello Macias in 
his first news conference said the events in Chiapas State have 
adversely affected Mexico's image abroad. Mexico was seen as a 
stable country where social stability prevailed, he said. Tello 
Macrias also said Mexico has not taken into consideration the 
possibility of requesting aid from the United States or any 
other government. Tello Macias said Peace Commissioner Manuel 
Camacho Solis is the only voice to explain what is being done, 
how it is being achieved, and what is expected of the 
reconciliation process. Let us listen to him: 
  [Begin Tello Macias recording] It would be advisable to 
avoid 
the proliferation of people playing the leading role in this 
situation. I believe it would be much better for the national 
and international public if there is only one voice. [end 
recording] 
  Manuel Tello described as serious the possibility that other 
governments are supporting the armed movement in Chiapas because 
they would be hurting the country's sovereignty. He said that 
even though there is no evidence, the Mexican Government does 
not rule out the possibility that non-Mexicans are participating 
in actions with the armed group. The Mexican foreign minister, 
who until a few days ago was Mexico's representative at the 
United Nations, said the Chiapas conflict adversely affects 
various sectors of the population but said it is no reason to 
paralyze the country. 

</TEXT>

