<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Social Liberation Party Threatens To Kill Five Human Rights Leaders </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1201160894 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1528 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1201160894 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 12 Jan (EFE) -- The clandestine Social 
Liberation Party, unknown until today, has threatened to kill 
five human rights organization leaders for not supporting the 
struggle of the Zapatist National Liberation Army (EZLN). 
  LA JORNADA newspaper reported today that it had received an 
anonymous telephone call, informing it of the existence of a 
message concerning the armed conflict in the southeastern state 
of Chiapas. The newspaper added that the message was later found 
on a utility pole on a Mexico City street. 
  The five threatened leaders belong to nongovernmental 
organizations and, according to the communique, are accused of 
"not supporting the armed struggle movement in Chiapas, and, in 
turn, they have betrayed the ideals of many struggling groups." 
  The threatened leaders are: Sergio Aguayo, president of the 
Mexican Human Rights Academy; Juan Carlos Martinez, coordinator 
of the Fray Francisco de Victoria Human Rights Center; Alejandro 
Camarillo, president of the Mexican Human Rights Commission; 
Fernando Ruiz Canales, president of the Law and Human Rights 
Council; and Victor Clark Alfaro, director of the Binational 
Human Rights Center. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

