<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   De Leon Announces Cabinet Changes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1901235494 Guatemala City Teleonce Television in Spanish 
1900 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1901235494 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City Teleonce Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Excerpt" of a news conference by Guatemalan President </F>
Ramiro de Leon Carpio on cabinet changes in Guatemala City on 19 
January; from the "Telepress" newscast; broadcast in progress -- 
recorded] 
  [Text] ...the task of directly studying and evaluating the 
performances of each of the state institutions, and as a state 
duty, I have been forced to make changes in the government 
cabinet which I consider necessary to strengthen or, as some 
news media have put it, to oxygenate the cabinet and government 
in general, thereby enabling them to function as a much stronger 
team. 
  Upon completing the necessary evaluations, I had to thank 
certain government employees for their cooperation, as in the 
case with Foreign Minister Arturo Fajardo Maldonado, who will be 
replaced by Marithza Ruiz de Vielman, based on her background, 
capabilities, and human and professional qualities. 
  In all the ministries I am going to mention, you can rest 
assured we conducted a flawless examination of the appointees, 
and that their appointments were based exclusively on the 
capabilities they have displayed in the numerous activities they 
have pursued, their qualifications, and especially their 
professional and human qualities and also, unquestionably, their 
performances in other disciplines or activities, public as well 
as private. 
  Engineer Oscar Armando Martinez Anaya, who was minister of 
communications, transportation, and public works, will be 
replaced by Eng. Jorge Erdmenger de la Fuente. The Economy 
Ministry, which soon we hope to be able to legally call by the 
name we are currently using, Foreign Trade Ministry, will be 
headed by Eduardo Gonzalez Castillo, replacing Fanny de Estrada, 
who resigned some time ago because of health problems. The 
Finance Ministry was and still is headed by Richard Aitkenhead, 
who presented his irrevocable resignation some time ago because 
he was appointed to an important position in an international 
organization. I spoke with Aitkenhead and after accepting his 
resignation I decided to replace him with Economist Ana Ordonez 
de Molina, who until now was executive secretary of the 
Presidency. Her appointment was based on the follow-up 
evaluation I referred to earlier. 
  As a strategy to strengthen the economic cabinet, Romulo 
Caballeros was secretary general of economic planning up until 
December. He accepted the position solely to participate in and 
cooperate with the government in the area of planning -- a 
mission he carried out perfectly because that institution worked 
with the economic cabinet on the 180-day plan and the 1994-95 
government agenda. Having fulfilled his goal, and since he is no 
longer with us, I have appointed Guillermo Rodriguez Magual as 
secretary general of economic planning. 

</TEXT>

