<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fujimori, U.S. Envoy Discuss Human Rights Situation </TI></H3>
<H4>   Fujimori Rejects Supreme Court Review </H4>
<F P=102> PA2101142094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0822 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2101142094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Lima, 21 Jan (EFE) -- Peruvian President Alberto 
Fujimori has rejected a U.S. request that the Supreme Court 
review terrorism cases tried by military courts. 
  Fujimori, who met with Alexander Watson, assistant secretary 
of state for Inter-American Affairs, justified his refusal to 
accept the U.S. proposal by noting, as as an example, that the 
top Shining Path leader Abimael Guzman "could be freed for lack 
of evidence" should the Supreme Court review his case. The 
review of terrorism trials "is a risk we cannot accept in the 
same way that the United States would not accept it if it were 
in our situation," the Peruvian chief of state added. Fujimori 
pointed out that the Judicial Branch is not yet "completely 
reformed" and that the civilian judicial system "is no guarantee 
that human rights will be respected." 
  Fujimori and Watson met at the Government Palace in Lima. It 
was a "constructive and frank," meeting according to the U.S. 
government official at its conclusion. [passage omitted] 
  Fujimori, for his part, expressed his confidence that the 
meeting has served to "dispel the doubts" of the United States 
about the human rights and democratization process. 
  Regarding democratization, the chief of state said he told 
the U.S. official "that the Peru that existed before 5 April 
1992 was not viable and that the measures adopted had been 
necessary." According to Fujimori, this "was a topic that was 
well understood" by the U.S. Government representative. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-51520 </DOCNO>
