<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fujimori, U.S. Envoy Discuss Human Rights Situation </TI></H3>
<H4>   Fujimori Terms Meeting `Positive' </H4>
<F P=102> PA2101151894 Lima Global de Television Network in Spanish 
0100 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2101151894 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima Global de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Global TV News" newscast] </F>
  [Excerpt] President Alberto Fujimori has met in private and 
for almost two hours at the presidential palace's Grau Room with 
U.S. Undersecretary Alexander Watson. The U.S. official arrived 
at Pizarro's home [presidential palace] at 1025 with U.S. 
Ambassador Alvin Adams. Three important issues were discussed 
during the meeting: the consolidation of democracy, the 
strengthening of human rights, and cooperation in the struggle 
against drug trafficking. After labelling as positive the 
meeting with Watson, the president reiterated that the 5 April 
[1992] measures had been necessary to prevent Peru from being 
totally undermined. Here is what President Fujimori said: 
  [Begin recording] On the democracy issue we have clearly 
pointed out that the Peru that existed before 5 April 1992, had 
no future. There was a need to take emergency measures to 
prevent Peru from being totally undermined. I have mentioned 
previously that this was a process that subsequently took place 
in Russia; unfortunately, as we all well know, there were many 
victims. Here, one-year plus, I would say instead that we have 
rescued democracy. This is an issue that has been widely 
discussed. 
  The second issue was in regard to the strengthening the 
defense of human rights. On this we have been categorical, I 
have made myself very clear here. What human rights are we 
talking about when terrorist violence overwhelmed the whole 
community and life was not worth one cent here? True, there are 
some isolated cases [of human rights violations], but now there 
is true respect for human rights. [end recording] [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

