<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mexico, Colombia Chosen Members of Opanal Council </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2101233194 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2313 GMT 19 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2101233194 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 19 Jan (NOTIMEX) -- Mexico and Colombia 
have been elected members of the Council of the Organization for 
the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons in Latin America (Opanal), 
the Mexican Foreign Secretariat announced today. 
  The election to a four-year term was conducted during 
Opanal's eighth extraordinary period of sessions, which was held 
at the Foreign Secretariat's conference room and chaired by 
Deputy Foreign Secretary Rosario Green. 
  At that forum, the official noted new Opanal Chairman 
Enrique 
Roman Morey's willingness to see that the continental agreements 
against the arms race are fully enforced, and he pledged to 
foster peace on the continent. 
  Green stressed that Argentina's and Chile's adherence to the 
Tlatelolco Treaty helped Opanal oversee the faithful compliance 
of this pact, which calls for banning nuclear weapons in Latin 
America and the Caribbean. 
  At the conclusion of the meeting, Ambassador Green hosted a 
lunch in honor of outgoing Opanal Chairman Antonio Stempel 
Paris, at which she noted his dedication and effort to free the 
continent of nuclear weapons. She recalled that the Mexican 
Government has granted top priority to achieving this goal. 

</TEXT>

