<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Elects Carles as Presidential Candidate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2301223394 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2108 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2301223394 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Panama City, 23 Jan (ACAN-EFE) -- The Nationalist 
Liberal Republican Movement (Molirena) elected today Ruben Dario 
Carles, former Panamanian comptroller general, its presidential 
candidate for the 8 May 1994 elections. 
  Carles--whom his opponents have accused of having obstructed 
the disbursement of budget funds for social programs while in 
the Comptroller General's Office--was elected by a majority vote 
at the Molirena national convention held at the convention 
center in the capital. 
  Molirena decided last night to cease supporting the 
government alliance which has led the country since 1989. This 
has prompted Panamanian President Guillermo Endara to announce 
that he will reshuffle his cabinet in view of the possible 
withdrawal of Molirena ministers from the government. 
  The path toward the election of the septuagenarian was 
cleared after Panamanian Vice President Guillermo Ford renounced 
during its convention his aspirations to be the presidential 
candidate for this political group. 
  Guillermo Guijano, the Molirena former housing minister who 
suffered heart problems in the past hours, was chosen first vice 
president candidate, and Tomas Herrera, of the Civic Renewal 
Party (PRC), was chosen for the second vice president slot. 
  Carles will be nominated by new right-wing parties, namely, 
the National Renewal Movement, PRC, and a faction of Popular 
Alliance (AP), led by former Mayor Mayin Correa, which were left 
out of the elections by the Electoral Tribunal (TE). 
  The Arnulfista Party (PA) also held its national convention 
today. This party, to which President Guillermo Endara belongs, 
elected as is presidential candidate Mireya Moscoso de Gruber, 
widow of Arnulfo Arias Madrid, a caudillo and three-time 
Panamanian president. 
  Moscoso, who is a novice in politics, is the sole female 
presidential candidate and will head a new alliance supported by 
the minority Authentic Liberal Party (PLA), the only remaining 
party of the 1989 opposition alliance. 
  PLA leader Arnulfo Escalona was nominated for the slot of 
first vice president, and Jose Teran, of the minority Liberal 
Party (PL), which was part of the previous military government, 
was chosen for the second vice president position. 
  These three parties were joined by other minority groups, 
namely, the Popular Nationalist Party (PNP), Independent 
Democratic Union (UDI), and an AP faction. A reply from the 
National Unity Mission (MUN), which objected to Escalona's 
candidacy, is expected. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-51560 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat015_j_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-015 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Confirms Support for Carles' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2301191094 Panama City EL PANAMA AMERICA in Spanish 23 Jan 
94 p 1a </F>

<F P=103> PA2301191094 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City EL PANAMA AMERICA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Juan Manuel Diaz C.] </F>
  [Text] The Molirena [Nationalist Liberal Republican 
Movement] party political committee decided unanimously to 
support [former Comptroller General] Ruben Dario Carles' 
presidential candidacy after negotiations to bring about an 
alliance with the Arnulfist Party [PA] failed. 
  Molirena President Alfredo Ramirez indicated that after 
several hours of deliberations the party's political committee 
decided to select Carles as the presidential candidate because 
he represented the best option. 
  Ramirez stated that, unfortunately, conversations with the 
PA 
had not progressed. For several months now Molirena has been 
stating its intention to participate in the May 1994 elections 
with its own candidate. At the same time, Ramirez pointed out 
that Molirena also seeks to occupy the first vice presidency of 
any ticket that supports Carles' candidacy. In order to 
accomplish this, it has designated a commission to prepare a 
list of nominees from which Carles can chose the person most 
suited to occupy the position of first vice president. 
  A Molirena source reported that possible first vice 
president 
nominees include former Labor Minister Jorge Ruben Rosas, former 
Housing Minister Guillermo Quijano, and National Assembly 
President Arturo Vallarino. According to the same source, Carles 
could opt for Guillermo Quijano as first vice president and 
Tomas Herrera, member [and president] of the Civic Renewal Party 
as second vice president. 
  As of today, Ruben Dario Carles' candidacy will be supported 
by three parties: National Renewal, Civic Renewal, and Molirena. 
  Meanwhile, First Vice President Guillermo Ford indicated 
that 
he will continue to carry out his duties as a member of 
President Endara's cabinet. At the same time he accepted the 
Molirena political committee's decision and reiterated that he 
plans to continue being a member of said party. Ford said that 
he will continue serving democracy until 1 September 1994 when 
the new government is expected to be inaugurated. The vice 
president stipulated that together with President Endara he 
expects to guarantee clean and fair elections as an aftermath of 
the administration elected in 1989. 
  On the other hand, it was disclosed that those cabinet 
ministers who are Molirena members have no plans to resign their 
current positions and indicated that they will step down if it 
is specifically requested by President Endara. 
  Molirena is expected to hold its national convention today 
at 
the ATLAPA Convention Center and to ratify the decision made by 
the party's political committee. The party is expected to hold 
internal elections on 30 January to select candidates for 
legislators, corregimiento representatives, mayors, and council 
representatives. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

